<Challenge Title="How Fast is the Flash?">
    <Text>
        In this challenge you will update your Circle Analyzer program to calculate how fast the
        flash can run around the Earth. To do this you will need to determine the circumference
        of the Earth and the speed at which the Flash can run.  
    </Text>

    <Note>
        <b>Hint:</b>
        <MudListItem Icon="@Icons.Filled.QuestionMark">The diameter of the Earth is 7917.5 miles!</MudListItem>
        <MudListItem Icon="@Icons.Filled.QuestionMark">The circumference of a circle is <Code>2 * pi * radius</Code></MudListItem>
        <MudListItem Icon="@Icons.Filled.QuestionMark">The Flash can run at 2,532 miles per hour!</MudListItem>
    </Note>

    <TaskItem Name="Three Floats">Add three <Code>float</Code> variables to your program: <Code>speed</Code>,<Code>circumference</Code>, and<Code>time</Code></TaskItem>
    <TaskItem Name="Prompt run speed">After the area of the circle is displayed, prompt the user "How fast can you run:"</TaskItem>
    <TaskItem Name="Parse Speed">Call <Code>float.Parse(Console.ReadLine())</Code> and store the result in the <Code>speed</Code> variable.</TaskItem>
    <TaskItem Name="Calculate Circumference">Calculate the <Code>circumference</Code> of the circle.</TaskItem>
    <TaskItem Name="Calculate Time">Calculate <Code>time</Code> as <Code>circumference / speed</Code></TaskItem>
    <TaskItem Name="Display Message Circumference">Display a message to the user letting them know the circumference of the circle</TaskItem>
    <TaskItem Name="Display Message Run Around">Display a message letting them know how long it take to run around the circle. </TaskItem>
    <TaskItem Name="Calculate Flash Speed">Finally, use your program to calculate how much time it would take for the Flash to run around the Earth</TaskItem>

</Challenge>